WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.720
Good afternoon, everyone. So I'll be talking about the intestinal microbiome and the impact

00:00:05.720 --> 00:00:12.920
of the intestinal microbiome on efficacy and toxicity in cell therapy. So we know that

00:00:12.920 --> 00:00:17.600
host extrinsic and host intrinsic factors impact the efficacy of cancer immunotherapy,

00:00:17.860 --> 00:00:24.740
both immune checkpoint blockade, but also now a real emerging data set in terms of the

00:00:24.740 --> 00:00:29.040
cell therapies, both with allotransplant and CAR-T cell therapy. For today's talk, I'm

00:00:29.040 --> 00:00:34.740
going to focus on one big factor that impacts the microbiome, medications, and specifically

00:00:34.740 --> 00:00:40.240
antibiotics that induce disruption to the microbiome called dysbiosis. And so I'll be

00:00:40.240 --> 00:00:45.280
discussing the antibiotic data in light of the gut microbiome and what we know about outcomes

00:00:45.280 --> 00:00:52.040
in terms of both allotransplant and CAR-T cell therapy. So here's just a brief overview of what

00:00:52.040 --> 00:00:57.520
I'll drill into in the talk, which is that antibiotic use in the setting of hematopoietic

00:00:58.080 --> 00:01:04.440
transplant and CAR-T cell therapy decreases commensal anaerobes, specifically when we give

00:01:04.440 --> 00:01:09.820
anaerobic targeting antibiotics. They alter the metabolome and decrease alpha and beta diversity

00:01:09.820 --> 00:01:15.940
of the microbiome, increase antibiotic resistance. And in the setting of allotransplant, data has

00:01:15.940 --> 00:01:20.580
shown that the exposure to these antibiotics is associated with increased graft-versus-host

00:01:20.580 --> 00:01:25.520
disease incidence and mortality, as well as increased antibiotic resistance. And for CAR-T

00:01:25.520 --> 00:01:27.120
cell therapy, it's been associated with decreased progression of the microbiome, and it's been

00:01:27.120 --> 00:01:31.280
associated with increased progression-free survival, overall survival, as well as a higher

00:01:31.280 --> 00:01:38.720
incidence of immune effector cell-associated neurotoxicity syndrome, or ICANS. So here is

00:01:38.720 --> 00:01:43.280
just a table summarizing some of the key studies that have evaluated antibiotic exposure and

00:01:43.280 --> 00:01:50.340
transplant outcomes. And you can see that I categorized into auto versus allo, the antibiotics

00:01:50.340 --> 00:01:56.160
that patients were exposed to, the sites where these studies were performed. Two of the studies,

00:01:56.160 --> 00:02:04.020
the first two, were prospective studies looking at antibiotic exposures, PIP-TASO or vanc and Cipro.

00:02:04.480 --> 00:02:09.960
And then the remainder were retrospective analyses looking at antibiotic exposure

00:02:09.960 --> 00:02:17.700
around various time points before and peri-engraftment, mostly. And the impact of

00:02:17.700 --> 00:02:23.520
these antibiotics in our transplant patient population has been decreasing neutropenic

00:02:23.520 --> 00:02:31.880
fever and also bacteremia. But also when you look at the lower half, focusing on carbapenems and

00:02:31.880 --> 00:02:36.500
piperacillin-tazobactam, which are both anaerobic-targeting antibiotics, meaning that they

00:02:36.500 --> 00:02:42.680
disrupt or deplete the anaerobic commensals in the gut, they've been associated with increased

00:02:42.680 --> 00:02:46.400
graft-versus-host disease, as well as GVHD mortality.

00:02:47.620 --> 00:02:52.700
One of these studies that was performed at Memorial Sun Kettering Cancer Center looked at antibiotic

00:02:52.700 --> 00:02:59.000
exposure between days minus seven to 28 post-transplant, and they looked at several

00:02:59.000 --> 00:03:05.160
antibiotics, so Astrionem, Cefepime, as control non-anaerobic-targeting antibiotics, and then

00:03:05.160 --> 00:03:12.060
Imipenem and PIP-TASO as anaerobic-targeting. And what they found was that exposure to Imi and

00:03:12.060 --> 00:03:18.880
PIP-TASO was associated with worse graft-versus-host disease mortality compared to those two controls,

00:03:18.880 --> 00:03:20.560
Astrionem and Cefepime.

00:03:21.600 --> 00:03:21.840
Dr. Debra Ruh

00:03:21.840 --> 00:03:21.920
Dr. Debra Ruh

00:03:21.920 --> 00:03:25.960
Several other studies have reported antibiotics associated with increased graft-versus-host

00:03:25.960 --> 00:03:31.900
disease, which I summarized there and which are all detailed in that review from Blood in 2024.

00:03:33.200 --> 00:03:40.580
This was not just phenomenology as it relates to PIP-TASO and Imipenem, because then they also

00:03:40.580 --> 00:03:48.500
looked in a mouse model of transplant and looked at bone marrow plus T-cells and Astrionem in a

00:03:48.500 --> 00:03:50.960
MHC-matched allotransplant.

00:03:51.920 --> 00:03:57.480
They found that the patients exposed to both Imipenem and PIP-TASO did worse.

00:03:57.800 --> 00:04:04.700
And I think this starts to get at the question that I often get asked and we also had, and you'll

00:04:04.700 --> 00:04:10.920
probably ponder as well when you see the CAR-T-cell data, that it's not just antibiotic exposure,

00:04:11.180 --> 00:04:16.020
but what the antibiotics are targeting that are driving these outcomes and differences in survival.

00:04:16.020 --> 00:04:21.020
Because when you see a survival curve showing that patients exposed to antibiotics do worse,

00:04:21.080 --> 00:04:25.040
you're automatically going to think, well, were those just sicker patients who got antibiotics

00:04:25.040 --> 00:04:28.720
and we're seeing those worse outcomes, it's a confounder?

00:04:28.720 --> 00:04:32.700
Or really, is there something about what the antibiotics are depleting in the gut

00:04:32.700 --> 00:04:34.760
that could be driving those outcomes?

00:04:35.400 --> 00:04:38.120
So now I want to change gears over to CAR-T-cell therapy.

00:04:38.240 --> 00:04:42.060
All of us are aware of the various CAR Ts that have been approved across indications.

00:04:42.920 --> 00:04:48.560
So in terms of this space, we know that antibiotic treatment is needed in the CAR-T-cell setting,

00:04:48.660 --> 00:04:50.860
similar to allotransplant patients or neutropenem.

00:04:51.080 --> 00:04:52.220
So we know that, again, our patients are neutropenic, they have fevers.

00:04:52.660 --> 00:05:00.740
Here's a retrospective analysis from Fred Hutch, where they looked at 517 patients who received

00:05:00.740 --> 00:05:08.340
CAR-T-cell therapy, and what they found just in summary was that, sorry, of the 694 patients in

00:05:08.340 --> 00:05:16.440
their cohort, 517, so over 90% had grade one or two CRS, but a fraction of those patients had

00:05:16.440 --> 00:05:17.200
bacteremia.

00:05:17.200 --> 00:05:20.740
So we know that, again, our patients are neutropenic.

00:05:21.080 --> 00:05:26.080
When they're going through CAR-T-cell therapy, have fever and CRS, we cannot withhold antibiotics.

00:05:26.600 --> 00:05:31.620
But being judicious about that antibiotic exposures, which ones we start, is really

00:05:31.620 --> 00:05:35.700
important to keep in mind, because only a fraction of these patients had a bacteremia

00:05:35.700 --> 00:05:39.920
that was driving their fever at the time of antibiotic exposure.

00:05:41.020 --> 00:05:44.580
So that brings me to our study that was published several years ago now.

00:05:44.580 --> 00:05:48.540
It was a collaboration between Memorial Sloan Kettering Cancer Center and the University

00:05:48.540 --> 00:05:49.160
of Pennsylvania.

00:05:49.780 --> 00:05:51.000
And we evaluated 200.

00:05:51.080 --> 00:05:54.260
28 patients who received CD19 CAR-T-cell therapy.

00:05:54.820 --> 00:06:00.220
We looked at any antibiotic exposure, and we did see that any antibiotic exposure in

00:06:00.220 --> 00:06:04.620
the four weeks prior to CAR-T-cell therapy was associated with decreased overall survival

00:06:04.620 --> 00:06:05.940
and progression-free survival.

00:06:05.940 --> 00:06:11.100
But knowing that not all antibiotics are equally damaging to the gut, we honed in on anaerobic

00:06:11.100 --> 00:06:15.400
targeting antibiotics, as I've already talked about, and we specifically focused on PIM,

00:06:15.480 --> 00:06:16.320
as noted there.

00:06:16.780 --> 00:06:20.940
And we found that exposure to PIM was associated with notable decrease in overall survival,

00:06:21.080 --> 00:06:28.340
as well as progression-free survival, when we stratified both by DLBCL or BALL alone.

00:06:29.740 --> 00:06:34.860
Subsequent to our publication now, two other studies have been published showing, again,

00:06:34.860 --> 00:06:39.680
that anaerobic antibiotic exposure is associated with decreased progression-free survival.

00:06:39.680 --> 00:06:44.980
One study shown here by Stein-Thoranger et al., which was a collaboration between Moffitt

00:06:44.980 --> 00:06:49.940
Cancer Center, MD Anderson, as well as three centers in Germany, showed that exposure to

00:06:50.120 --> 00:06:53.940
high-risk antibiotics was associated with a decreased proportion for survival.

00:06:54.480 --> 00:07:00.440
Subsequently, another study that looked more broadly at cephalosporins, as well as any anaerobic

00:07:00.440 --> 00:07:04.680
targeting antibiotics, again found that anaerobic targeting antibiotic exposure was associated

00:07:04.680 --> 00:07:07.180
with a decreased progression-free survival.

00:07:08.340 --> 00:07:12.120
And so summarizing the data to date, there have now been five studies that have been

00:07:12.120 --> 00:07:17.900
published, primarily looking at CD19 CAR-T-cell exposure, and looking at various time

00:07:17.900 --> 00:07:19.680
points pre-CAR-T-cell exposure.

00:07:19.940 --> 00:07:24.380
We know that many of our patients are going to be exposed to antibiotics after CAR for

00:07:24.380 --> 00:07:25.700
CAR toxicity.

00:07:25.700 --> 00:07:29.980
You can see that these antibiotics have been linked with worse survival, and in two of

00:07:29.980 --> 00:07:35.920
them, they've also been linked to increased incidence of ICANs.

00:07:35.920 --> 00:07:41.920
These studies have also identified overlapping bacterial taxa in patients exposed to CD19

00:07:41.920 --> 00:07:46.320
CAR-T-cell therapy, and I'm only showing bacteria that have been identified in more than one

00:07:46.320 --> 00:07:47.320
study.

00:07:47.320 --> 00:07:48.280
So, several candidates for mechanistic cytotoxicity.

00:07:48.280 --> 00:07:49.240
So, I'm going to stop here.

00:07:49.240 --> 00:07:49.240
Thank you very much.

00:07:49.240 --> 00:07:49.320
Thank you.

00:07:49.320 --> 00:07:56.760
studies. And in animal models, this has been validated. In one study recently published,

00:07:56.880 --> 00:08:02.380
they found that exposure to meropenem in an immunocompetent mouse model A20, which is a

00:08:02.380 --> 00:08:08.960
lymphoma model, mice treated with CD19 CAR-T-cells but administered meropenem in the days prior to

00:08:08.960 --> 00:08:15.360
CAR-T-cell therapy had worse survival. And another study in terms of preclinical evidence,

00:08:15.940 --> 00:08:21.180
mice were given a fecal microbiota transplant from responders or non-responders of CAR-T-cell

00:08:21.180 --> 00:08:26.240
therapy. And they found that the FMT from the responders was able to recapitulate response

00:08:26.240 --> 00:08:31.780
in the BALB-C, again, an immunocompetent mouse model. And then in a more recent study,

00:08:31.780 --> 00:08:36.800
they identified that acromantia, which is a bacteria acromantia species,

00:08:37.400 --> 00:08:43.560
was noted in those who had a more favorable response. And then when they drilled down and

00:08:43.560 --> 00:08:45.900
used a mouse model that had...

00:08:45.940 --> 00:08:52.400
AHR or basically the tryptophan pathway knocked out, they saw that it was AHR dependent. And so

00:08:52.400 --> 00:08:56.520
again, now we're already starting to drill down into mechanisms as to how the microbiome

00:08:56.520 --> 00:09:02.440
may be modulating CAR-T-cell phenotype. So with that, I would like to summarize that

00:09:02.440 --> 00:09:06.680
anaerobic targeting antibiotics, peritransplant is associated with higher rates of graft-versus-host

00:09:06.680 --> 00:09:12.100
disease, GDHG-related mortality, and reduced neutropenic fever and bacteria. In the CAR-T-cell

00:09:12.100 --> 00:09:15.920
setting, it's been associated with shorter PFS and OS, as well as improved immune response.

00:09:15.940 --> 00:09:21.000
Increased incidence of ICANS. And we now have candidate bacterial species in both of these

00:09:21.000 --> 00:09:25.700
settings that have been linked with clinical outcomes. And preclinical models are now needed

00:09:25.700 --> 00:09:29.080
to investigate regulatory mechanisms. Thank you so much.
